[3]
Date: Wed, 18 Sep 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Asahi Shimbun, 13 Sep 2002 [edited]
<http://www.asahi.com/english/feature/K2002091300392.html>


Japan: a year after/BSE blues
-----------------------------
In the year since mad cow disease was first discovered in Japan, the
government has spent enormous sums of taxpayers' money to win back
the public's trust in the meat industry. But part of the plan was
like putting a fox in charge of hen-house security. Greedy companies
suddenly found blank checks dangling in front of their noses, leading
to scandals involving mislabeled meat.

And when the mysterious nature of mad cow disease is thrown into the
mix, it is little wonder the traditionally finicky Japanese public
still harbors doubts about the safety of beef. "Once a problem
surfaces, people tend to become worried about this and that. Behind
such a mentality is probably the sense of public unease since the end
of the 20th century about science and technology," said Tatsuhiro
Kamisato, an expert on science history at the Tokyo-based Research
Institute of Science and Technology for Society. Kamisato said public
concerns are exacerbated by the "black boxes" in which food is
processed. He said consumers have no idea what happens to food before
it reaches the dinner plate.

After Japan's first case of bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE),
or mad cow disease, surfaced on 10 Sep last year, Tokyo spent 151
billion yen (1.22 billion USD) for a variety of BSE-related programs
and subsidies.

In contrast, Britain, which has had as many as 180 000 BSE cases so
far, used the equivalent of around 70 billion yen in 2000 to dispose
of all cattle aged 30 months or older and remove risky portions such
as brains and spinal cords from the meat-processing production.

Japan has confirmed 5 cases of BSE, while in Britain about 1000
infected cattle are still discovered annually.

But Japan's enormous funding has backfired in some ways. Major
companies Snow Brand Foods Co. and Japan Meat Packers Inc. disguised
imported meat as domestic to make it eligible for the
government-funded buyback program intended to help businesses hit by
the BSE scare. Instead of helping to restore consumer confidence, the
companies tried illegally take a piece of the 26.3 billion yen (213.6
million USD) earmarked for the buyback program.

Furthermore, the government's enormous expenditures have not produced
the desired results from a scientific standpoint. Testing of all dead
cattle, considered indispensable in determining how BSE is spread,
has yet to start.

In Japan, 70 000 cattle die each year of natural causes or illnesses.
The government said it will test all the dead animals but has so far
examined only 700 in sampling tests that began in April 2001, months
before the first BSE case was discovered. Meanwhile, the European
Union, which has tested all dead cattle aged 2 years or older since
July 2001, found 30 times more BSE infections among dead cattle than
in healthy animals.

Japan still has no idea how BSE, once considered a European problem,
infected Japanese cattle. Cattle feed called meat-and-bone-meal
(MBM), made from internal organs, bones, and scrap meat of
slaughtered cows, is widely blamed for the spread of the disease. But
the government does not know how and when the tainted MBM entered
Japan. About the only thing known so far is that a risky batch of MBM
was imported around 1990, before the British government restricted
exports of the product.

Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Ministry officials have found
that MBM production procedures in Italy before June 1998 were
insufficient and could have led to the spread of the disease in
Japan. They have also raised suspicions over Netherlands-produced
animal fat used in substitute milk, which was later fed to Japanese
cattle. But no substantial link has been confirmed. Experts believe
the spread of BSE is part of a cycle in which infected cattle are
processed into MBM. Cattle fed this MBM become infected with the
disease. If these new cattle are turned into MBM, the cycle starts
over.

The first infected Japanese cow was in either the second or third
turn of the cycle, the experts say. But they still have no clear
answers on how far the infection has spread. As of 31 Aug 2002, 4 of
1 057 811 slaughtered Japanese cattle were found to have been
infected since all-out testing started 18 Oct 2001. The Health, Labor
and Welfare Ministry, which is in charge of the procedure, plans to
test all cattle for human consumption. The ministry will request 4
billion yen (32.5 million USD) for the tests in the fiscal 2003
budget.

The ministry plans to have prefectural facilities carry the bulk of
the testing load, since only 4 institutions, such as the National
Institute of Infectious Disease, are equipped to conduct detailed
examinations of suspicious cases. Inspectors from 17 prefectural
governments have been trained for such testing, prompting one
ministry official to say the program "is now on track."

But Kazuya Yamanouchi, an expert on infectious diseases and a
professor emeritus at the University of Tokyo, said: "There is no
scientific proof that you need to test cattle aged 2 years or
younger, because BSE cannot be detected in young animals. The all-out
testing should be reviewed with the public's approval. We still have
no idea how the infection has been transmitted, and testing of all
dead cattle is indispensable for studying the path of infection.
Also, we cannot deny that the current situation is the result of a
repeated cycle of BSE that entered Japan. We need to do an
epidemiological study on this."

Although Japan is the only Asian country where BSE has been
confirmed, mad cow disease appears to be spreading globally. The
World Organization for Animal Health (OIE) said new cases of BSE have
been reported in Israel and Poland this year. As of Aug 2002, mad cow
disease had infected cattle in 22 countries.

Concerns in Asia are mounting because only a few nations are capable
of conducting their own tests on BSE, according to Yoshihiro Ozawa,
special adviser to the OIE. He pointed out that the EU has found a
higher rate of infection among sick and dead cattle than in healthy
ones. The same is likely to occur in Japan after the government gets
around to testing, he said.

"Japan could very well find around 13 BSE cases among dead and sick
cattle. Given the fact that ranchers are holding back shipments of
old cattle, it's not unnatural to think that the number could be
around 20," Ozawa said. "We need to have an idea as soon as possible
of how the BSE-infected cattle are dispersed around Japan. The longer
we put it off, the longer it will take us to get rid of the BSE
problem."

