<http://agri3.huji.ac.il/~yakobson/bse/>


Israel: BSE testing according to source and age groups
------------------------------------------------------
The Israeli veterinary services publish on a weekly basis the results
of the applied active BSE testing of fallen cattle. Since 1 Jul 2002,
all slaughtered cattle, over 30 months, have been added to the
testing scheme. The weekly report is signed by the Head, Department
of Pathology, KVI.

The following data are derived from the last weekly report,
presenting the accumulated numbers of tested cattle according to age
groups (in years), for the period 1 Jan - 11 Sep 2002:

1. Fallen cattle received at the central incineration facility,
Western Galilee:
2-3 / 3-4 / 4-5 / 5+/ total
30 / 75 / 68 / 208 / 381

2. Slaughtered cattle in abattoirs (from 1 Jul 2002 - including all
cattle over 30 months):
2-3 / 3-4 / 4-5 / 5+ / n.a. / total
78 / 291 / 567 / 1500 / 176 / 2612

3. Cattle with CNS symptoms, sent to the department of pathology in
KVI: total 28.

Grand total since 1 Jan 2002: 3021.

The national Israeli herd includes approx. 110 000 multiparous dairy cattle.

[The import to Israel of mammal MBMs from the UK was banned in 1988,
and from all countries since 1990. Since 1996, rendering of mammal
material was stopped altogether, and treatment of cadavers and
slaughterhouse waste was subsequently performed by burial. In 2001, a
central incineration facility became operational, currently receiving
most fallen stock and animal waste. Feeding of MBMs from mammal
origin to all food animals (mammals, avians, fish) was banned in
1996. Since July 2001, the feeding of poultry and fish meals to
mammalian food-animals has been banned as well.

Laboratory (passive) surveillance for BSE was initiated in 1992 by
histopathological examinations, performed in bovine brains of CNS
suspects at the KVI. Active surveillance was initiated in 1994; in
1997, immunochemistry was added to the lab arsenal. Since Jan 2001,
an intensified surveillance scheme has become operational, covering
fallen stock in addition to CNS suspects, while the rapid
Prionic-check BSE became the standard technique; histochemistry is
applied in inconclusive cases.

A case of BSE in a dairy cow, born in 1992, was diagnosed in June
2002. - Mod AS].

