[6]
Date: Tue, 17 Sep 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>


The following data have been included in a presentation by Marcus
Clauss & Ellen Kienzle at the Joint Nutrition Symposium, Antwerp, 21
- 25 Aug 2002 (Abstract book, p 56). The Symposium included the
following scientific institutions:

AAVN : American Academy of Veterinary Nutrition
ACVN : American College of Veterinary Nutrition
CNS : Comparative Nutrition Society
ECVCN : European College of Veterinary and Comparative Nutrition
ESVCN : European Society of Veterinary and Comparative Nutrition
EZNRG : European Zoo Nutrition Research Group

Feeding practices in the German BSE inquiry; An oral presentation.

Evaluation of feeding practices in Bavarian BSE herds; the presented
data, based upon investigations of 82 confirmed BSE cases, were
obtained from 2 sources:
1. epidemiological questionnaire answered by the farmer;
2. copies of money transfer receipts of feedingstuff purchases.

Results:
1.
Q: Was Calf Milk Replacer (CMR) used? (Information from 79 cases).
A: Yes - 69 percent; No - 4 percent; No information available (NIA) -
27 percent.

2.
Q: Was CMR purchased? (Documentation from 82 cases).
A: Yes - 75 percent; No - 2 percent; No documentation available (NDA)
- 23 percent.

3.
Q: Did calves receive pelleted feed? (Information from 79 cases).
A: Yes - 58 percent; No - 22 percent; NIA - 20 percent.

4.
Q: Have Calf starter pellets been purchased? (Documentation from 82 cases).
A: Yes - 51 percent; No - 26 percent; NDA - 23 percent.

5.
Q: What combinations of CMR and commercial feeds (CF) for calves were
used? (Information from 79 cases).
A: CMR and CF - 48 percent; CMR, no CF - 19 percent; CF, no CMR - 3
percent; neither - 1 percent; NIA - 29 percent.

6.
Q: Did calves, which received exclusively CMR, get additional mineral
supplements? (Information from 20 cases . See 19 percent "CNR - no
CF" in Answer 5 above).
A: Yes - 20 percent; No - 40 percent; Unknown - 40 percent.

7.
Q: Did farms, where calves received exclusively CMR, buy feed for
other species? (Documentation from 20 cases - see 19 percent "CNR -
no CF" in Answer 5 above).
A: Yes - 50 percent; No - 50 percent.

Concluding remarks:
Open questions - Is there another route of (oral) infection than
meat&bone meal?
or
Is the assumed incubation period overestimated?

Authors:
Prof. Dr. Ellen Kienzle
Dr. Marcus Clauss
Institute of Animal Physiology, Physiological Chemistry and Animal Nutrition
Veterinary Faculty of Munich, Germany
<clauss@tiph.vetmed.uni-muenchen.de>

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-mail is grateful to the authors for sharing with us their
observations.]

[The results of the Bavarian field investigation, while inconclusive,
do not exclude CMRs as a possible infection source (see previous postings).
It is extremely difficult to sort out facts and activities from several
years ago not recorded at the time, based on a rather limited number of
available cases. Any details on continued surveillance projects and similar investigations in other BSE-affected countries would increase the number of
analyzed cases and consequently the significance of the results. - Mod AS].
